11 Q. Roscii: Q. Roscius Gallus was born near Lanuvium and died shortly before the delivery of Cicero's speech pro Archia (62 B. c.). He was by common consent, the greatest comio actor whom Rome produced, the intimate friend of Sulla, Hortensius and espe- cially of Cicero, whose teacher he is said to have been (Plut. Cic. 5) and whose speech in his behalf (68 Β. o.) is still extant. His art, the result of the most painstaking care and the profoundest study (hence called ³ doctus Roscius ' by Hor. Ep. II 1, 82) was deemed so perfect that his name became proverbial for excellence in general (Cic. de orat. I 28, 130 Brut. 84, 290 Festus p. 289 Μ.). Accord- ing to Macrob. Sat. ΙΙ 10, he was the author of a work in which the art of acting and of oratory was compared, and Diomed. G. L. Ι 489, on the authority probably of Varro, says that Roscius was the first to introduce masks upon the Roman stage, an innovation which Donatus, Praef. Ter. Eun. p. 10 R., however, dates as far back as Ambivius Turpio. The studied refinement and dignity which the Ciceronian period admired in Roscius and his great contemporary, the tragedian Aesopus, appeared old-fashioned‚ stilted and artificial in an age whose taste had been vitiated by the realistic acting of the pantomime. Cp. Friedlander II 445 f. Aper's criticism may possibly have been directly suggested by Cic. de orat.
